{"slug": "augur", "root": "augur", "category": "divination", "gloss": "divination by the flight/behaviour of birds", "definition": "An augur was a Roman priest who read the will of the gods in the flight and feeding of birds; *augury* is the art. To augur is to foretell from signs.", "history": "Latin *augur* named the official who took the *auspices* (*avis*, 'bird,' + *specere*, 'to look') before any public act; the word may link to *augēre*, 'to increase, to bless.' The ritual survives fossilized in *inauguration* — we still 'inaugurate' by taking good omens. Magic keeps *augury* as flavor for its blue and white seers, and made 'Augur' a recurring card name.", "def_sources": [{"label": "Etymonline, s.v. augur", "where": "Etymology reference"}, {"label": "RenaissanceMagicDB (divination context)", "where": "RenaissanceMagicDB"}], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"origin": "Latin augur, a Roman priest who read bird-signs; perhaps from augere ‘to increase, bless’", "first": "late 14c.", "note": "The augurs read the flight of birds to bless state actions; ‘inauguration’ still carries the ritual.", "hook": "Why presidents are ‘inaugurated’ — by bird-omen.", "lang": "Latin"}, "essay": null, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_total": 13, "oracle_total": 1, "in_flavor_cards": 13, "in_oracle_cards": 1, "name_match_count": 29, "by_variant": {"augur": 11, "augurs": 3}, "first_year": 1997, "colors": {"B": 13, "R": 4, "U": 24, "C": 2, "W": 5, "G": 4}, "by_year": {"1997": 1, "2003": 1, "2007": 5, "2008": 1, "2010": 1, "2011": 2, "2013": 1, "2014": 1, "2015": 2, "2016": 1, "2017": 2, "2019": 1, "2020": 4, "2021": 5, "2022": 4, "2023": 2, "2024": 6, "2025": 2}}, "cards": [{"id": "df9409e6-bd6d-4b5b-b807-fcf347ee940a", "name": "Glarb, Calamity's Augur", "set": "BLB", "type_line": "Legendary Creature — 